Acute coronary syndromes in patients with HIV.

Seecheran VK(1), Giddings SL, Seecheran NA.

Author information:
(1)aDepartment of Adult Medicine, The University of the West Indies, St. 
Augustine bDepartment of Adult Medicine, The North West Regional Health 
Authority, Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago.

Highly active antiretroviral treatment (HAART) has considerably increased the 
life expectancy of patients infected with HIV. Coronary artery disease is a 
leading cause of mortality in patients infected with HIV. This is primarily 
attributed to their increased survival, HAART-induced metabolic derangements, 
and to HIV itself. The pathophysiology of atherosclerosis in HIV is both 
multifactorial and complex - involving direct endothelial injury and 
dysfunction, hypercoagulability, and a significant contribution from traditional 
cardiac risk factors. The advent of HAART has since heralded a remarkable 
improvement in outcomes, but at the expense of other unforeseen issues. It is 
thus of paramount importance to swiftly recognize and manage acute coronary 
syndromes in HIV-infected patients to attenuate adverse complications, which 
should translate into improved clinical outcomes.

